    "summary": "The Shunga Dynasty (185–73 BC) was an Indian dynasty that ruled the Gangetic plain and central India after overthrowing the last [[event:74|Maurya Empire]] emperor, notable for its revival of Brahmanical Hinduism and patronage of Buddhist art despite reportedly persecuting Buddhism in some regions.\n\nFounded by Pushyamitra Shunga, a Brahmin general who assassinated Emperor Brihadratha during a military parade, the dynasty maintained control of the Magadha heartland and Pataliputra. The Shungas repelled an invasion by the [[event:1104|Indo-Greek Kingdom]] under Menander I and consolidated their rule over much of northern India, though their empire was smaller than the Mauryan predecessor. Paradoxically, some of the finest Buddhist monuments — including the gateways at Sanchi — date to the Shunga period, suggesting that religious patronage was more complex than accounts of persecution imply. The dynasty gradually declined as feudatories broke away and was replaced by the Kanva dynasty around 73 BC.",
